{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506881"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2581"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.24,0.27,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient receiving treatment for giant cell arteritis is being reviewed. Their treatment consists of 40mg prednisone in the morning and 100mg aspirin. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, previously managed with metformin monotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrior to prednisolone, the patient had reasonable glycaemic control, ranging ~6-10 mmol/L throughout the day. Now, his current blood glucose levels (BGLs) are ~7-9 mmol/L fasted in the morning, and ranging 15-24 mmol/L before lunch and dinner, higher in the late afternoon.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his blood glucose levels whilst an inpatient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isophane insulin mane (e.g. Protaphane)","Gliclazide immediate release mane","Insulin glargine mane (e.g. Optisulin, previously Lantus)","Insulin degludec 70%/insulin apart 30% twice daily (e.g. Ryzodeg)","Actrapid three times daily with meals"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a common inpatient scenario where someone with previously well-controlled diabetes mellitus is initiated on a glucocorticoid regimen, and there is subsequently difficult to control hyperglycaemia. Glucocorticoids induce hyperglycaemia through multiple channels including insulin resistance and impaired release. Typical morning steroid administration causes a blood glucose peak post-prandial after lunch. The key treatment for very elevated BGL (\u003E15) is insulin, regardless of whether the patient was on insulin previously. This question focuses on the different types of insulin and their onset/duration of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid acting insulin\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. insulin lispro [humalog], insulin aspart [novorapid]) have onset within 15-20 minutes, peak at 1 hour and duration of effect lasts 3.5-4.5 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort acting insulins\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. regular insulin [actrapid]) have onset in 30 minutes, peak effect at 1-3 hours and duration of 8 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermediate acting insulins\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. isophane insulin [protaphane]), have onset at 1.5 hours, peak effect at 4-12 hours and duration ~18 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong acting insulins\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. insulin glargine [optisulin] or detemir [levemir]) have onset within 1 hour, with minimal peak but continued effect for 24 hour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltra-long acting insulins\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. insulin glargine U300 [Toujeo] or degludec) have onset with in 1-2 hours and last for more than 24 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith the BGL peak associated with steroid use occurring 4-6 hours after administration, \u003Cstrong\u003Eisophane (protaphane)\u003C/strong\u003E is the ideal agent matching its peak effect at this time. Further, due to its shorter duration of action compared to long-acting insulins (18 hours versus 24 hours) it has less propensity to cause early morning hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s morning BGLs are relatively well controlled, and a morning dose of prednisolone should not significantly impact overnight BGLs, a long-acting insulin such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eglargine (optisulin)\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Edegludec\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurthermore, given the very long duration of action of \u003Cstrong\u003Edegludec\u003C/strong\u003E (up to 72 hours) found in mixed insulin \u003Cstrong\u003ERyzodeg,\u003C/strong\u003E this mediation is difficult to titrate up or down quickly, as could be required with a rapidly changing glucocorticoid regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESupplementary insulin with \u003Cstrong\u003Eregular insulin (actrapid)\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered to assist in BGL management, but given the glucocorticoid has caused hyperglycaemia consistently throughout the day, a single insulin injection that will act over the same duration as the steroid is a more preferred option. Should intermediate-acting insulin alone be ineffective, introduction of actrapid could be considered as adjunctive therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGliclazide immediate-result\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in glucocorticoid-exacerbated hyperglycaemia; however, the magnitude of its effects are modest, and unlikely to adequately address the significant prandial hyperglycaemia noted in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, specialist endocrine advice should be sought with complex patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucocorticoid-induced hyperglycaemia typically peaks 4-6 hours after morning steroid administration, requiring insulin therapy that matches this pattern.","Intermediate-acting insulin (isophane) is the preferred choice for steroid-induced hyperglycaemia as its peak effect coincides with the steroid-induced glucose peak.","Long-acting insulins are less suitable for steroid-induced hyperglycaemia as they lack a peak effect and may cause early morning hypoglycaemia."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Management of type 2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP, 2020.","Burtun R. Breaking Down Barriers to Insulin Use [Powerpoint]. Waitakere Hospital: WDHB; 2011 [cited 12 May 2021]. Available from: http://www.gpcme.co.nz/pdf/2011ROT/Thursday/5-DownerWorks/1430%20Burtun%20-%20Breaking%20the%20Barriers%20to%20Insulin%20use%20changes%202%20as%20at%2028-10-2010.pdf.","Australian Diabetes Society. Guidelines for routine glucose control in hospital. 2012; Australia [cited 12 May 2021]. Available from: https://diabetessociety.com.au/documents/ADSGuidelinesforRoutineGlucoseControlinHospitalFinal2012.pdf.","Smith JH, Swanson JW. Giant Cell Arteritis. Headache; 2014: 54(8) 1273-1289.","Oyer DS, Shah A, Bettenhausen S. How to manage steroid diabetes in the patient with cancer. Journal of Supportive Oncology 2006;4(9):479-83."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T14:37:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-21T14:41:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel